urrent lighting and appliances (I am surprised that the US lighting is as high as 20%, my figures are more UK oriented but there we are!) <br>
<br>
My Suggestion is that improvements in efficiency are unlikely to result in reduced consumption Rather what will/has happened is that consumption has remained static while “Standard of living” has gone up. <br>
<br>
Unfortunately this has damaged the economics of electricity production and has resulted in a decline in long-term projects in favour of low cost, high profit, short-term solutions that are unlikely to be of much use to us in the future!<br>
<br>
An additional point is that, at least in the UK, there is rarely any such thing as *wasted* energy. For most of the year we benefit from some form of space heating, especially in the evening, sometimes even in mid summer! <br>
<br>
The likely result is that whatever advantage is gained by the high efficiency fridge or the low energy light bulb (Which I don’t use because they are not powerful enough and wont work with dimmer switches) is lost by greater use of electric heaters. (Most people wont fire up the cental heating in the summer months, but they will switch on an electric fire!)<br>
<br>
